<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 6:20<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If58158f16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I1c3ad730933c11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>6.</label.designator><headtext>Selection of a Transferee District</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94f486d6e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>6:20.</label.designator><headtext>Factors articulated by the Panel in selecting transferee district—District where jurisdiction available</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel has considered personal jurisdiction questions in selecting a transferee district.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If581a7106b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] This factor is a difficult one to evaluate, for it is clear that the Panel can transfer actions for coordinated or consolidated pretrial proceedings in a district where personal jurisdiction over all the parties may not exist.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If581a7116b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>This factor may be relevant where transfer under <cite.query w-src-number="0304914081" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1404" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I72f257e06b3e11e99779f698461214a6">28 U.S.C.A. § 1404(a)</cite.query> is likely and the Panel&apos;s decision merely anticipates this result. <eos/><bos/>In that circumstance, transfer by the Panel to a district where jurisdiction over the defendants can be obtained increases overall efficiency by simplifying the transfer process, since transfer under <cite.query w-src-number="0304914081" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1404" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I72f257e16b3e11e99779f698461214a6">28 U.S.C.A. § 1404(a)</cite.query> may only be to a district having jurisdiction over the parties.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If581ce206b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">3</footnote.reference>] Similarly, if the Panel anticipates that additional related actions will be filed, selection of a transferee district where the jurisdiction lies may encourage new actions to be originally filed in that district. <eos/><bos/>This would then obviate consideration of the actions as tag-along actions by the Panel.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If581ce226b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">4</footnote.reference>] In one case the Panel selected a district as a transferee district one in which the greatest number of actions could include all the defendants in order to maximize the collateral estoppel effect of a decision there.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If581f5306b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If58158f16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If581a7106b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See, e.g.</ital>, <cite.query w-src-number="0304914081" w-serial-number="1975105295" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="576" ID="I72f146716b3e11e99779f698461214a6">In re Highway Acc. Near Rockville, Connecticut, on December 30, 1972, 388 F. Supp. 574, 576 (J.P.M.L. 1975)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If581a7116b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See, e.g.</ital>, <cite.query w-src-number="0304914081" w-serial-number="1970113934" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="63" ID="I72f1bba16b3e11e99779f698461214a6">In re Air Crash Disaster Near Hanover, N. H., 314 F. Supp. 62, 63 (J.P.M.L. 1970)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0304914081" w-serial-number="1969103964" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" ID="I72f1bba36b3e11e99779f698461214a6">In re Library Editions of Children&apos;s Books, 299 F. Supp. 1139 (J.P.M.L. 1969)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If581ce206b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304914081" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1404" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I72f27ef06b3e11e99779f698461214a6">28 U.S.C.A. § 1404(a)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The statute is set forth at <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs3:19" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If581ce216b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 3:19</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If581ce226b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Tag-along actions are discussed in Chapter 8.</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If581f5306b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304914081" w-serial-number="1972104795" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="382" ID="I72f342416b3e11e99779f698461214a6">In re Yarn Processing Patent Validity Litigation, 341 F. Supp. 376, 382 (J.P.M.L. 1972)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 6:20<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
